To establish a trust boundary where all incoming DSCP values from the Internet are rewritten to zero (default) on Cisco and Juniper routers, apply the following configurations:

Cisco IOS Configuration:
Apply a policy-map to the inbound interface of the WAN connection to reset DSCP values.

Policy Map:
```bash
policy-map MARKDOWN
 class class-default
  set dscp default
```

Interface Configuration:
```bash
interface gig 0/1
 service-policy input MARKDOWN
```

Juniper JunOS Configuration:
Apply rewrite rules within the interface unit configuration.

```bash
interfaces {
    so-1/2/3 {
        unit 0 {
            rewrite-rules {
                dscp default;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

To establish a trust boundary where incoming DSCP values are rewritten to zero (Best-Effort) on Cisco and Juniper routers, specific Class of Service (CoS) configurations are required on the LAN interfaces facing the internal network.

**Juniper (Junos) Configuration:**
A custom rewrite rule can be applied to interfaces to map all incoming traffic to a specific forwarding class. Two methods are described:

*Method 1: Direct Rewrite to Best-Effort*
Apply a rewrite rule on the LAN units that maps all traffic to the `best-effort` forwarding class. This class is configured with low loss priority.

```junos
# show class-of-service
interfaces {
    ge-1/1/0 {
        unit 4 {
            rewrite-rules {
                dscp internet;
            }
        }
    }
    ge-1/1/1 {
        unit 4 {
            rewrite-rules {
                dscp internet;
            }
        }
    }
}
rewrite-rules {
    dscp internet {
        forwarding-class best-effort {
            loss-priority low code-point be;
            loss-priority high code-point be;
        }
        forwarding-class network-control {
            loss-priority high code-point be;
            loss-priority low code-point be;
        }
    }
}
```

*Method 2: Conditional Rewrite (Non-Zero DSCP Only)*
This method applies a custom classifier to WAN interfaces to identify non-zero DSCP values and applies a rewrite rule on LAN interfaces to drop or reset those specific values. The classifier `dscp internet` matches all DSCP code-points from 0x00 to 0xFF.

```junos
[edit class-of-service]
#
# Apply classifier to WAN interfaces (e.g., unit 0, 1, 3)
interfaces {
    ge-1/1/0 {
        unit 0 {
            classifiers {
                dscp internet;
            }
        }
        unit 1 {
            classifiers {
                dscp internet;
            }
        }
        unit 3 {
            classifiers {
                dscp internet;
            }
        }
        unit 4 {
            rewrite-rules {
                dscp internet;
            }
        }
    }
    ge-1/1/1 {
        unit 3 {
            classifiers {
                dscp internet;
            }
        }
        unit 4 {
            rewrite-rules {
                dscp internet;
            }
        }
    }
}

# Define the classifier matching all DSCP values
classifiers {
    dscp internet {
        forwarding-class best-effort {
            loss-priority low code-points [ 000000 000001 000010 000011 000100 000101 000110 000111 001000 001001 001010 001011 001100 001101 001110 001111 010000 010001 010010 010011 010100 010101 010110 010111 011000 011001 011010 011011 011100 011101 011110 011111 100000 100001 100010 100011 100100 100101 100110 100111 101000 101001 101010 101011 101100 101101 101110 101111 110000 110001 110010 110011 110100 110101 110110 110111 111000 111001 111010 111011 111100 111101 111110 111111 ];
        }
    }
}

# Apply rewrite rule to LAN interfaces (e.g., unit 4)
rewrite-rules {
    dscp internet {
        forwarding-class best-effort {
            loss-priority high code-point be;
        }
    }
}
```

**Cisco Configuration:**
While the provided text focuses on Juniper, the concept for Cisco IOS-XE/NX-OS involves applying a `trust boundary` on the ingress interface. This is typically done by configuring `mls qos trust dscp` on the WAN interface to accept the incoming values, and then applying a `rewrite` action or policy-map on the LAN interface to strip the DSCP value (setting it to 0) before traffic enters the internal QoS hierarchy. Alternatively, configuring the trust boundary on the LAN interface itself (`no mls qos trust dscp`) ensures all ingress traffic is treated as default (DSCP 0) regardless of incoming markings.

